data.content:
## What happened

In C# 14, new **span conversions** cause `array.Contains(num)` to bind to `MemoryExtensions.Contains(Span<T>, T)` instead of `Enumerable.Contains<T>(IEnumerable<T>, T)`. Expression trees cannot represent `Span`-based method calls, so compilation succeeds but the compiled expression **throws at runtime**.

## How to fix

Cast the array to `IEnumerable<T>` (or call `.AsEnumerable()`) to force the `Enumerable.Contains` overload:

```csharp
// Option 1: AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Option 2: Explicit static invocation
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

The same issue affects `Enumerable.Reverse` on arrays (now resolves to the in-place `Span` extension). Use `Enumerable.Reverse(arr)` explicitly in those cases too.
